te=4 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181205103609/https://www.news18.com/news/movies/shamshera-ranbir-kapoor-vaani-kapoors-film-goes-on-floors-1956175.html|archive-date=5 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left; background:#ffc;\"|''[[Jayeshbhai Jordaar]]''{{dagger|alt=Films that have not yet been released}}\n|2020\n| {{sortname|Divyang|Thakkar}}\n| [[Ranveer Singh]], [[Shalini Pandey]]\n| TBA\n|<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.dnaindia.com/bollywood/report-jayeshbhai-jordaar-ranveer-singh-and-shalini-pandey-head-to-gujarat-for-second-schedule-2808704|title='Jayeshbhai Jordaar': Ranveer Singh and Shalini Pandey head to Gujarat for second schedule|date=9 January 2020|accessdate=19 January 2020|work=Daily News and Analysis}}</ref>\n\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"  style=\"text-align:left; background:#ffc;\"|''[[Prithviraj (film)|Prithviraj]]''{{dagger|alt=Films that have not yet been released}}\n|2020\n| {{sortname|Chandraprakash|Dwivedi}}\n| [[Akshay Kumar]], [[Manushi Chhillar]]\n| TBA\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/amp/movies/bollywood/story/akshay-kumar-and-manushi-chhillar-start-prithviraj-with-hawan-here-s-to-auspicious-beginnings-1619285-2019-11-15|title=Akshay Kumar and Manushi Chhillar start Prithviraj with hawan: Here's to auspicious beginnings|accessdate=15 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/taran_adarsh/status/1195269181492432897|title=Filming begins... Akshay Kumar and Manushi Chhillar along with director Dr Chandraprakash Dwivedi performed pooja, before commencing the shooting of Yash Raj\u2019s historical film #Prithviraj... #Diwali2020 release.|accessdate=15 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"  style=\"text-align:left; background:#ffc;\"|''[[Sandeep Aur Pinky Faraar]]''{{dagger|alt=Films that have not yet been released}}\n|2020\n| {{sortname|Dibakar|Banerjee|nolink=yes}}\n| [[Parineeti Chopra]], [[Arjun Kapoor]]\n| TBA\n| <ref>{{cite news|title=Posters out! Sandeep Aur Pinky Faraar set to release on March 20|url=https://www.mid-day.com/amp/articles/posters-out-sandeep-aur-pinky-faraar-set-to-release-on-march-20/22653240|work=Mid Day|date=3 March 2020|accessdate=3 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n\n|}\n\n==Films distributed==\nIn addition to the films produced by Yash Raj Films since 1997,<ref name=\"distribution\"/> the following films from other banners were distributed, in domestic and/or overseas markets, by the company:<ref>{{cite web|title=YRF Distributes |url=http://www.yashrajfilms.com/Movies/MovieArchive.aspx |publisher=Yash Raj Films |accessdate=28 December 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141202150202/http://yashrajfilms.com/Movies/MovieArchive.aspx |archivedate= 2 December 2014 }}</ref>\n\n{{columns-list|colwidth=20em|\n* ''[[Kuch Kuch Hota Hai]]'' (1998)\n* ''[[Biwi No.1]]'' (1999)\n* ''[[Mann (film)|Mann]]'' (1999)\n* ''[[Godmother (film)|Godmother]]'' (1999)\n* ''[[Jaanwar (1999 film)|Jaanwar]]'' (1999)\n* ''[[Kaho Naa... Pyaar Hai]]'' (2000)\n* ''[[Dulhan Hum Le Jayenge]]'' (2000)\n* ''[[Refugee (2000 film)|Refugee]]'' (2000)\n* ''[[Deewane]]'' (2000)\n* ''[[Gaja Gamini]]'' (2000)\n* ''[[Zubeidaa]]'' (2001)\n* ''[[Aashiq (2001 film)|Aashiq]]'' (2001)\n* ''[[Kabhi Khushi Kabhie Gham...]]'' (2001)\n* ''[[Supari (film)|Supari]]'' (2003)\n* ''[[Main Prem Ki Diwani Hoon]]'' (2003)\n* ''[[Koi... Mil Gaya]]'' (2003)\n* ''[[Kal Ho Naa Ho]]'' (2003)\n* ''[[Maqbool]]'' (2004)\n* ''[[Meenaxi: A Tale of Three Cities]]'' (2004)\n* ''[[Charas: A Joint Operation]]'' (2004)\n* ''[[Gayab]]'' (2004)\n* ''[[Black (2005 film)|Black]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[Sins (film)|Sins]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[My Brother\u2026Nikhil]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[Kaal (2005 film)|Kaal]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[Mangal Pandey: The Rising]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[Maine Gandhi Ko Nahin Mara]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[Yaaran Naal Baharan]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[Krrish]]'' (2006)\n* ''[[Kabhi Alvida Naa Kehna]]'' (2006)\n* ''[[Krazzy 4]]'' (2008)\n* ''[[Dostana (2008 film)|Dostana]]'' (2008)\n* ''[[All the Best: Fun Begins]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[Chhota Bheem and the Throne of Bali]]'' (2013)\n* ''[[D-Day (2013 film)|D-Day]]'' (2013)\n* ''[[Aa Gaye Munde U.K. De]]'' (2014)\n* ''[[Happy New Year (2014 film)|Happy New Year]]'' (2014)\n* ''[[Piku]]'' (2015)\n* ''[[Tubelight (2017 Hindi film)|Tubelight]]'' (2017)\n* ''[[Jab Harry Met Sejal]]'' (2017)\n* ''[[Ittefaq (2017 film)|Ittefaq]]'' (2017)\n* ''[[Race 3]]'' (2018)\n* ''[[Teefa in Trouble]]'' (2018)\n* ''[[Hanuman vs Mahiravana]]'' (2018)\n* ''[[Loveyatri]]'' (2018)\n* ''[[Zero (2018 film)|Zero]]'' (2018)\n* ''[[Notebook (2019 film)|Notebook]]'' (2019)\n* '' [[Chhota Bheem Kung Fu Dhamaka]]'' (2019)\n* ''[[De De Pyaar De]]'' (2019)\n* ''[[Saaho]]'' (2019)\n* ''[[Dabangg 3]]'' (2019)\n* ''[[Jai Mummy Di]]'' (2020)\n* ''[[Malang (film)|Malang]]'' (2020)\n* ''[[Radhe (2020 film)|Radhe]]'' (2020)\n* ''[[Chhalaang]]'' (2020)\n}}\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{notelist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.yashrajfilms.com/}}\n* {{IMDb company|0077190|Yash Raj Films}}\n* [http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movies/company/type/view/id/38622 Yash Raj Films] at [[Bollywood Hungama]]\n\n{{Yash Raj Films}}\n\n{{featured list}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yash Raj Films, List of films released by}}\n[[Category:Yash Raj Films]]\n[[Category:Yash Raj Films films]]\n[[Category:Lists of Bollywood films]]\n[[Category:Lists of films by studio]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2017}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2017}}\n[[File:Yash Chopra 2012.jpg|thumb|[[Yash Chopra]], the founder of [[Yash Raj Films]], pictured in 2012. He directed 13 films for the company between 1973 and 2012.|alt=Yash Chopra is standing with his hands in his pockets, and looking away from the camera]]\n\n[[Yash Raj Films]] (abbreviated as YRF) is an Indian entertainment company, established by [[Yash Chopra]] in 1970, that [[film production|produces]] and [[film distribution|distributes]] motion pictures.<ref name=\"Punathambekar2013\">{{cite book|last=Punathambekar |first=Aswin |title=From Bombay to Bollywood: The Making of a Global Media Industry |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nsiyynyoZ1AC&pg=PA195 |date=24 July 2013 |publisher=NYU Press |isbn=978-0-8147-7189-1 |pages=195\u2013197 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170404230405/https://books.google.com/books?id=nsiyynyoZ1AC&pg=PA195 |archivedate= 4 April 2017 }}</ref><ref name=\"results\">{{cite news|last=Bhushan |first=Nyay |title=Yash Chopra: Producing results |url=https://hollywoodreporter.com/news/yash-chopra-producing-results-89812 |date=8 October 2009 |accessdate=30 December 2014 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150208053915/https://hollywoodreporter.com/news/yash-chopra-producing-results-89812 |archivedate= 8 February 2015 }}</ref> As of 2019, the company has produced 78 [[Bollywood|Hindi]] films, including three that are yet to be released, and one [[Tamil Cinema|Tamil]] film. Yash Raj Films started a film distribution business in 1997,<ref name=\"distribution\">{{cite book|title=Business of Cinema.com |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Gq_LrAjaiJ8C&pg=PA36 |date=March 2008 |publisher=Join The Dots Media Pvt. Ltd. |page=28 |id=GGKEY:QKBD4RDWLXK |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170404230950/https://books.google.com/books?id=Gq_LrAjaiJ8C&pg=PA36 |archivedate=2017-04-04 }}</ref> and in addition to distributing their own productions, the company has handled the domestic and/or international distribution of over 40 films from other companies.\n\nYash Raj Films' first release came in 1973 with the Chopra-directed ''[[Daag: A Poem of Love]]'', a drama about [[bigamy]], starring [[Rajesh Khanna]], [[Raakhee]] and [[Sharmila Tagore]].<ref name=\"Chintamani2014\">{{cite book|last=Chintamani |first=Gautam |title=Dark Star: The Loneliness of Being Rajesh Khanna |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5AuiBQAAQBAJ&pg=PT76 |date=15 September 2014 |publisher=HarperCollins Publishers India |isbn=978-93-5136-340-8 |pages=76\u201378 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170406201141/https://books.google.com/books?id=5AuiBQAAQBAJ&pg=PT76 |archivedate= 6 April 2017 }}</ref> The company had four more releases in the 1970s, including the family drama ''[[Kabhie Kabhie (1976 film)|Kabhie Kabhie]]'' and the action film ''[[Kaala Patthar]]'', both of which starred [[Amitabh Bachchan]].<ref name=\"Gulaz\u0101raNihalani2003\">{{cite book|last1=Gulzar |last2=Nihalani |first2=Govind |last3=Chatterjee |first3=Saibal |title=Encyclopaedia of Hindi Cinema |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8y8vN9A14nkC&pg=PT565 |year=2003 |publisher=Popular Prakashan |isbn=978-81-7991-066-5 |page=565 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140103081204/http://books.google.com/books?id=8y8vN9A14nkC&pg=PT565 |archivedate=2014-01-03 }}</ref> Yash Raj Films' sole commercial success in the 1980s was the [[Sridevi]]-starring romance ''[[Chandni]]''.<ref name=\"Gulaz\u0101raNihalani2003\"/> The year 1995 marked the directorial debut of Aditya Chopra with the highly successful romantic drama ''[[Dilwale Dulhania Le Jayenge]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boxofficeindia.com/cpages.php?pageName=all_time_earners|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120107103929/http://boxofficeindia.com/cpages.php?pageName=all_time_earners|archivedate=7 January 2012|title=All Time Grossers|publisher=[[Box Office India]]|accessdate=13 May 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Somaaya2008\">{{cite book|last=Somaaya |first=Bhawana |title=Fragmented Frames: Reflections of a Critic |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HQ3Yi9VPU8QC&pg=PP114 |date=1 January 2008 |publisher=Pustak Mahal |isbn=978-81-223-1016-0 |page=114 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170406203948/https://books.google.com/books?id=HQ3Yi9VPU8QC&pg=PP114 |archivedate= 6 April 2017 }}</ref> Starring [[Shah Rukh Khan]] and [[Kajol]], the film has the longest theatrical run in Indian cinema history.<ref name=\"ddlj\">{{cite web |title='DDLJ' to complete 1000 weeks at Maratha Mandir theatre on Friday |url=http://ibnlive.in.com/videos/517598/ddlj-to-complete-1000-weeks-at-maratha-mandir-theatre-on-friday.html |publisher=[[CNN-IBN]] |date=11 December 2014 |accessdate=11 December 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6Yu78Daiu?url=http://www.ibnlive.com/videos/india/ddlj-1000-weeks-730712.html |archivedate=30 May 2015 }}</ref> Other successful releases of the 1990s were ''[[Darr]]'' (1993) and ''[[Dil To Pagal Hai]]'' (1997), both starring Khan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=126&catName=MTk5MC0xOTk5|title=Top Lifetime Grossers 1990\u20131999 (Figures in Ind Rs)|publisher=Box Office India|accessdate=13 January 2014|date=1 January 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131014072959/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=126&catName=MTk5MC0xOTk5|archivedate=14 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn the 2000s, Yash Raj Films produced a larger number of films. In addition to directorial ventures from Yash and Aditya Chopra, the company launched several new directors, including [[Sanjay Gadhvi]], [[Vijay Krishna Acharya]], [[Kunal Kohli]], [[Siddharth Anand]], and [[Shaad Ali]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Jain |first=Priyanka |title=Come on, show me the money! |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/entertainment/bollywood/come-on-show-me-the-money/article1-888451.aspx |work=[[Hindustan Times]] |date=13 July 2012 |accessdate=30 December 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129023613/http://www.hindustantimes.com/entertainment/bollywood/come-on-show-me-the-money/article1-888451.aspx |archivedate=29 November 2014 }}</ref> Some of the company's top-grossing films in that decade include Gadhvi's action thrillers ''[[Dhoom]]'' (2004) and ''[[Dhoom 2]]'' (2006), Kohli's romantic thriller ''[[Fanaa (film)|Fanaa]]'' (2006), Ali's comedy film ''[[Bunty Aur Babli]]'' (2005), Yash Chopra's romance ''[[Veer-Zaara]]'' (2004), and Aditya Chopra's dramas ''[[Mohabbatein]]'' (2000) and ''[[Rab Ne Bana Di Jodi]]'' (2008).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=127&catName=MjAwMC0yMDA5|title=Top Lifetime Grossers 2000\u20132009 (Figures in Ind Rs)|publisher=Box Office India|accessdate=13 January 2014|date=1 January 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131014070531/http://boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=127&catName=MjAwMC0yMDA5|archivedate=14 October 2013}}</ref> Beginning in 2008, the company introduced a number of new actors such as [[Anushka Sharma]], [[Ranveer Singh]], [[Parineeti Chopra]], and [[Arjun Kapoor]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Yash Raj Films to launch newcomers every two years|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Yash-Raj-Films-to-launch-newcomers-every-two-years/articleshow/12729717.cms|work=[[The Times of India]]|date=19 April 2012|accessdate=30 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180407193022/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Yash-Raj-Films-to-launch-newcomers-every-two-years/articleshow/12729717.cms|archive-date=7 April 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nYash Raj Films' highest-grossing films came in the 2010s with the spy thriller ''[[Ek Tha Tiger]]'' (2012) and its [[Tiger Zinda Hai|2017 sequel]], both starring [[Salman Khan]] and [[Katrina Kaif]], the third installment of the [[Dhoom (film series)|''Dhoom'' franchise]], entitled ''[[Dhoom 3]]'' (2013), featuring [[Aamir Khan]], [[Uday Chopra]] and [[Abhishek Bachchan]], the sports drama ''[[Sultan (2016 film)|Sultan]]'' (2016), starring Salman Khan and Anushka Sharma , and the action thriller ''[[War (2019 film)|War]]'' (2019), starring [[Hrithik Roshan]] and [[Tiger Shroff]]. All five films rank among the [[List of highest-grossing Bollywood films|highest-grossing Indian films of all time]].<ref name=\"dhoom\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/boxnewsdetail.php?page=shownews&articleid=6355&nCat|title=Dhoom 3 All Time Number One Worldwide Grosser: 500 cr Plus Expected|publisher=Box Office India|accessdate=13 January 2014|date=1 January 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140102192306/http://boxofficeindia.com/boxnewsdetail.php?page=shownews&articleid=6355&nCat|archivedate=2 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://boxofficeindia.com/report-details.php?articleid=2166 |title=Sultan Hits 500 Crore Worldwide |publisher=Box Office India |accessdate=21 July 2016 |date=18 July 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160723183210/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/report-details.php?articleid=2166 |archivedate=23 July 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://boxofficeindia.com/report-details.php?articleid=3621 |title=Tiger Zinda Hai Set To Be 3rd Highest Nett Grosser Ever |publisher=Box Office India |accessdate=27 January 2017 |date=27 January 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180127203030/http://boxofficeindia.com/report-details.php?articleid=3621 |archive-date=27 January 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> The most frequent collaborations of the company have been with the actors [[Rani Mukerji]], [[Rishi Kapoor]], [[Shah Rukh Khan]], Anushka Sharma, Katrina Kaif, [[Saif Ali Khan]], and Parineeti Chopra.\n\n==Films produced==\n[[File:Rakhee Gulzar.jpg|right|thumb|150px|[[Raakhee]] played the lead female role in four of the five productions of Yash Raj Films in the 1970s]]\n[[File:Amitabh Bachchan December 2013.png|right|thumb|150px|[[Amitabh Bachchan]] has collaborated with Yash Raj Films on six projects, playing leading roles in three of them]]\n[[File:Rishi Kapoor.jpg|right|thumb|150px|[[Rishi Kapoor]] has collaborated with Yash Raj Films on ten projects{{efn|name=rishi|This does not include a guest appearance in ''[[Jab Tak Hai Jaan]]''.<ref>{{cite news|last=Malani|first=Gaurav|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Jab-Tak-Hai-Jaan-Yash-Chopras-immortal-love-story/articleshow/17205991.cms|title=Jab Tak Hai Jaan: Yash Chopra's immortal love story|accessdate=31 December 2014|work=The Times of India|date=13 November 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161108015735/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Jab-Tak-Hai-Jaan-Yash-Chopras-immortal-love-story/articleshow/17205991.cms|archive-date=8 November 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>}}]]\n[[File:Sridevi.jpg|right|thumb|150px|[[Sridevi]] played the title role in Yash Raj Films' most successful film of the 1980s {{mdash}} ''[[Chandni]]'' (1989)<ref name=\"Gulaz\u0101raNihalani2003\"/>]]\n[[File:Shahrukh interacts with media after KKR's maiden IPL title.jpg|right|thumb|150px|[[Shah Rukh Khan]] has worked with Yash Raj Films on nine projects, beginning with ''[[Darr]]'' (1993)]]\n[[File: Hrithik at Rado launch.jpg|right|thumb|150px|[[Hrithik Roshan]] has worked with Yash Raj Films on 3 successful projects, beginning with ''[[Mujhse Dosti Karoge!]]'' (2002)]]\n[[File:Kajol at Dilwale press conference.jpg|right|thumb|150px|[[Kajol]] played the lead role in ''[[Dilwale Dulhania Le Jayenge]]'' (1995) {{mdash}} the film with the longest theatrical run in Indian cinema history.<ref name=\"ddlj\"/>]]\n[[File:Rani Mukerji 2009 (2).jpg|right|thumb|150px|[[Rani Mukerji]] has worked with Yash Raj Films on twelve projects, beginning with ''[[Mujhse Dosti Karoge!]]'' (2002)]]\n[[File:Preity Zinta at an event for ISHKQ IN PARIS.jpg|right|thumb|150px|[[Preity Zinta]] starred in three of the company's productions in the 2000s]]\n[[File:Abhi 2013.jpg|right|thumb|150px|[[Abhishek Bachchan]] played the lead role in the [[Dhoom (film series)|''Dhoom'' franchise]]  (2004\u201313)]]\n[[File:Saif at 2014 Stardust.jpg|right|thumb|150px|[[Saif Ali Khan]] has played leading roles in seven of the company's films]]\n[[File:Anushka pk special screening for tendulkar and thackeray.jpg|right|thumb|150px|[[Anushka Sharma]] made her acting debut with ''[[Rab Ne Bana Di Jodi]]'' (2008), and has since starred in seven other Yash Raj Films' projects]]\n[[File:Katrina Kaif 2011.jpg|right|thumb|150px|[[Katrina Kaif]] has collaborated with Yash Raj Films on seven projects, beginning with ''[[New York (2009 film)|New York]]'' (2009)]]\n[[File:Ranveer Singh at Sahara Star New Year's bash press meet2.jpg|right|thumb|150px|[[Ranveer Singh]] made his acting debut with ''[[Band Baaja Baaraat]]'' (2010) after which he worked with the company four more times]]\n[[File:Parineeti Chopra inaugurates a school on wheels (03).jpg|right|thumb|150px|[[Parineeti Chopra]] has collaborated with Yash Raj Films on seven projects, including her debut film ''[[Ladies vs Ricky Bahl]]'' (2011)]]\n[[File:Arjun Kapoor at the 59th Filmfare Pre-Awards Party.jpg|right|thumb|150px|[[Arjun Kapoor]] made his acting debut with ''[[Ishaqzaade]]'' (2012) and has since worked with the company three more times]]\n[[File:Vaani Kapoor from Befikre promotion.jpg|right|thumb|150px|[[Vaani Kapoor]] made her acting debut with ''[[Shuddh Desi Romance]]'' (2013) and has collaborated with the company on four more films]]\n[[File:Aamir Khan 2013.jpg|right|thumb|150px|[[Aamir Khan]] has starred in two top-grossing films of the company, ''[[Fanaa (film)|Fanaa]]'' (2006) and ''[[Dhoom 3]]'' (2013)]]\n[[File:Salman Khan at Renault Star Guild Awards.jpg|right|thumb|150px|[[Salman Khan]] has starred in three of the company's highest-grossing releases, including the two films in the [[Tiger (franchise)|''Tiger'' film series]]]]\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Key\n| style=\"background:#ffc;\"| {{dagger|alt=Films that have not yet been released}}\n| Denotes films that have not yet been released\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\" style=\"width: 81%; text-align: center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | T