mmy Di]]'' (2020)\n* ''[[Malang (film)|Malang]]'' (2020)\n* ''[[Radhe (2020 film)|Radhe]]'' (2020)\n* ''[[Chhalaang]]'' (2020)\n}}\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{notelist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.yashrajfilms.com/}}\n* {{IMDb company|0077190|Yash Raj Films}}\n* [http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movies/company/type/view/id/38622 Yash Raj Films] at [[Bollywood Hungama]]\n\n{{Yash Raj Films}}\n\n{{featured list}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yash Raj Films, List of films released by}}\n[[Category:Yash Raj Films]]\n[[Category:Yash Raj Films films]]\n[[Category:Lists of Bollywood films]]\n[[Category:Lists of films by studio]]\n", "name_user": "64.40.230.100", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_films_released_by_Yash_Raj_Films"}
{"title_page": "List of Dharma Productions films", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n[[File:Karan Johar walks the ramp for Shane and Falguni Peacock.jpg|thumb|upright=1.0|[[Karan Johar]], the son of [[Yash Johar]], has directed six films for [[Dharma Productions]].]]\n\n[[Dharma Productions]] is an Indian production company established by [[Yash Johar]] in 1976.<ref name=\"Punathambekar2013\">{{cite book|last=Punathambekar |first=Aswin |title=From Bombay to Bollywood: The Making of a Global Media Industry |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nsiyynyoZ1AC&pg=PA73 |date=24 July 2013 |publisher=NYU Press |isbn=978-0-8147-7189-1 |pages=73\u201374 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161223173459/https://books.google.com/books?id=nsiyynyoZ1AC&pg=PA73 |archivedate=23 December 2016 }}</ref> As of 2020, the company has produced 52 [[Bollywood|Hindi films]], including seven that have yet to be released. A large number of the films were co-produced with companies such as [[UTV Motion Pictures]], [[Red Chillies Entertainment]] and [[Fox Star Studios]]. In addition, Dharma Productions has presented five [[Cinema of India#Regional industries|regional language films]] from other companies.\n\nDharma Productions' first release came in 1980 with the [[Raj Khosla]]\u2013directed ''[[Dostana (1980 film)|Dostana]]'', starring [[Amitabh Bachchan]], [[Shatrughan Sinha]] and [[Zeenat Aman]], which was a commercial success.<ref>{{cite web|title=Yash Johar, in memoriam |url=http://specials.rediff.com/movies/2004/jun/28sld5.htm |publisher=[[Rediff.com]] |date=28 June 2004 |accessdate=16 February 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150216100317/http://specials.rediff.com/movies/2004/jun/28sld5.htm |archivedate=16 February 2015 }}</ref> However, their subsequent releases, ''[[Duniya (1984 film)|Duniya]]'' (1984) and ''[[Muqaddar Ka Faisla]]'' (1987) performed poorly at the box office.<ref name=\"yashjoharfilm\">{{cite web|last=Verma |first=Sukanya |title=A Yash Johar film! |url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/2004/jun/29sld1.htm |publisher=Rediff.com |date=29 June 2004 |accessdate=16 February 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150216180600/http://www.rediff.com/movies/2004/jun/29sld1.htm |archivedate=16 February 2015 }}</ref> Their first release of the 1990s, the Bachchan-starring thriller ''[[Agneepath (1990 film)|Agneepath]]'' (1990) garnered critical acclaim but was a commercial failure.<ref>\n{{cite news|last=KBR|first=Upala|title=Agneepath broke my father's heart: Karan Johar|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Agneepath-broke-my-fathers-heart-Karan-Johar/articleshow/11628129.cms|work=[[The Times of India]]|date=26 January 2012|accessdate=16 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180103193334/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Agneepath-broke-my-fathers-heart-Karan-Johar/articleshow/11628129.cms|archive-date=2018-01-03|url-status=live}}\n</ref> The company's next releases were the thriller ''[[Gumrah (1993 film)|Gumrah]]'' (1993) and the comedy ''[[Duplicate (1998 film)|Duplicate]]'' (1998), both directed by [[Mahesh Bhatt]].<ref name=\"yashjoharfilm\"/> In 1998, Yash Johar's son, [[Karan Johar]] made his directorial debut with the romantic comedy-drama ''[[Kuch Kuch Hota Hai]]'', starring [[Shah Rukh Khan]], [[Kajol]], [[Rani Mukerji]] and [[Salman Khan]]. The film was the highest-grossing Bollywood film of 1998, and established Dharma Productions as a leading production company in India.<ref>{{cite news|last=Bhattacharya |first=Roshmilla |title=My name is Karan |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/news-feed/entertainment/my-name-is-karan/article1-550682.aspx |work=[[Hindustan Times]] |date=30 May 2010 |accessdate=16 February 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150217212625/http://www.hindustantimes.com/news-feed/entertainment/my-name-is-karan/article1-550682.aspx |archivedate=17 February 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Box Office 1998 |url=http://boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=204&catName=MTk5OA== |publisher=[[Box Office India]] |accessdate=14 October 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131014095801/http://boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=204&catName=MTk5OA%3D%3D |archivedate=14 October 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Their subsequent releases, the ensemble melodrama ''[[Kabhi Khushi Kabhie Gham...]]'' (2001), the tear-jerking romantic drama ''[[Kal Ho Naa Ho]]'' (2003) and the musical romantic drama ''[[Kabhi Alvida Naa Kehna]]'' (2006), all starring Khan, were popular among the Indian diaspora worldwide and emerged as top-grossing Hindi films in domestic and overseas sales.<ref name=\"QuaysonDaswani2013\">{{cite book|last1=Quayson|first1=Ato |author1link=Ato Quayson|last2=Daswani|first2=Girish |title=A Companion to Diaspora and Transnationalism|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=arAEssNjsf4C&pg=RA8-PT29|date=3 July 2013|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=978-1-118-32064-8|page=8}}</ref><ref name=\"overseas\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/cpages.php?pageName=overseas_earners |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130905204607/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/cpages.php?pageName=overseas_earners|archivedate=5 September 2013|title=Overseas Earnings (Figures in Ind Rs)|publisher=Box Office India|accessdate=13 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2008 onwards, in addition to directorial ventures from Karan Johar, the company introduced several new directors, including [[Ayan Mukerji]], [[Punit Malhotra]], [[Karan Malhotra]], and [[Shakun Batra]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Talent should not have a gender: Karan Johar |url=http://www.deccanherald.com/content/331120/talent-should-not-have-gender.html |work=[[Deccan Herald]] |date=8 May 2013 |accessdate=16 February 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150216100406/http://www.deccanherald.com/content/331120/talent-should-not-have-gender.html |archivedate=16 February 2015 }}</ref> The romantic comedy ''[[Dostana (2008 film)|Dostana]]'' (2008) was the first mainstream Hindi film to take a homosexual storyline.<ref name=\"Dudrah2012\">{{cite book|last=Dudrah|first=Rajinder Kumar |title=Bollywood Travels: Culture, Diaspora and Border Crossings in Popular Hindi Cinema|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mWD1N-J9JSoC&pg=PA43|year=2012|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-0-415-44740-9|pages=43\u201346}}</ref> In 2012, Karan Johar directed the teen romance ''[[Student of the Year]]'', which marked the debut of actors [[Sidharth Malhotra]], [[Varun Dhawan]] and [[Alia Bhatt]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Karan Johar: I feel I am film institute of India |url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/karan-johar-i-feel-i-am-film-institute-of-india/ |work=[[The Indian Express]] |date=13 June 2014 |accessdate=16 February 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150216113451/http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/karan-johar-i-feel-i-am-film-institute-of-india/ |archivedate=16 February 2015 }}</ref> The following year, the company co-produced the critically acclaimed drama ''[[The Lunchbox]]'', which was nominated for the [[BAFTA Award for Best Film Not in the English Language]].<ref>{{cite web|title=BAFTA: 'Boyhood' wins top honours, 'The Lunchbox' misses award |url=http://zeenews.india.com/entertainment/movies/bafta-boyhood-wins-top-honours-the-lunchbox-misses-award_1543627.html |publisher=[[Zee News]] |date=9 February 2015 |accessdate=16 February 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150209235117/http://zeenews.india.com/entertainment/movies/bafta-boyhood-wins-top-honours-the-lunchbox-misses-award_1543627.html |archivedate= 9 February 2015 }}</ref> Dharma Productions' greatest successes in the 2010s came with the social drama ''[[My Name Is Khan]]'' (2010); the 2012 [[Agneepath (2012 film)|remake of ''Agneepath'']]; the romantic dramas ''[[Yeh Jawaani Hai Deewani]]'' (2013), ''[[2 States (2014 film)|2 States]]'' (2014), ''[[Ae Dil Hai Mushkil]]'' (2016), and ''[[Badrinath Ki Dulhania]]'' (2017); the family drama ''[[Kapoor & Sons]]'' (2016); the spy film ''[[Raazi]]'' (2018); the action comedy ''[[Simmba]]'' (2018); and the comedy ''[[Good Newwz]]'' (2019).<ref name=\"top2010\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/boxnewsdetail.php?page=shownews&articleid=4378&nCat=|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120509154836/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/boxnewsdetail.php?page=shownews&articleid=4378&nCat=|archivedate=9 May 2012 |title=Top Worldwide Grossers |publisher=Box Office India |date=7 May 2012 |accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/box-office-special-features/box-office-worldwide-collections-day-wise-break-raazi/|title=Box Office: Worldwide collections and day wise break up of Raazi|publisher=Bollywood Hungama|accessdate=2 June 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180512105652/http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/box-office-special-features/box-office-worldwide-collections-day-wise-break-raazi/|archivedate=12 May 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"alltime\">{{cite web |url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/worldwide-total-gross.php |title=Top Worldwide Grossers All Time |publisher=Box Office India |accessdate=13 January 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161016064410/http://boxofficeindia.com/worldwide-total-gross.php |archivedate=16 October 2016 }}</ref><ref>\n{{cite web|url=https://boxofficeindia.com/report-details.php?articleid=4599|title=Simmba Hits Huge Number Worldwide|date=4 January 2019|website=Box Office India|accessdate=4 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190104175531/https://boxofficeindia.com/report-details.php?articleid=4599|archive-date=2019-01-04|url-status=live}}\n</ref> The most frequent collaborations of the company have been with the actors Alia Bhatt, Shah Rukh Khan, Sidharth Malhotra, [[Kareena Kapoor]], Amitabh Bachchan, [[Ranbir Kapoor]], Kajol, Varun Dhawan, and [[Sanjay Dutt]].\n\n==Films produced==\n[[File:Amitabh Bachchan 2014.jpg|right|thumb|150px|[[Amitabh Bachchan]] has collaborated with Dharma Productions on five projects, beginning with their first release ''[[Dostana (1980 film)|Dostana]]'' (1980).]]\n[[File:Sanjay Dutt at Mumbai Airport, 2018 (cropped).jpg|right|thumb|150px|[[Sanjay Dutt]] has starred in four of the company's films.]]\n[[File:Shahrukh interacts with media after KKR's maiden IPL title.jpg|right|thumb|150px|[[Shah Rukh Khan]] has played leading roles in seven Dharma Productions films.]]\n[[File:Kajol, Kelvinator Stree Shakti Women Awards 2014 (cropped).jpg|right|thumb|150px|[[Kajol]] has played leading roles in four Dharma Productions films.]]\n[[File:Kareena kapoor vaio launch.jpg|right|thumb|150px|[[Kareena Kapoor]] has collaborated with the company on six projects.]]\n[[File:Akshay Kumar.jpg|right|thumb|150px|[[Akshay Kumar]] has played leading roles in four Dharma Productions films.]]\n{{multiple image\n| align     = right\n| direction = vertical\n| image1    = Sidharth Malhotra 2016.jpg\n| alt1      =\n| image2    = Varun Dhawan Stardust Conference.jpg\n| alt2      =\n| image3 = Alia Bhatt promoting Kalank.jpg\n| alt3 =\n| footer    = [[Sidharth Malhotra]] (top), [[Varun Dhawan]] (middle) and [[Alia Bhatt]] (bottom) made their acting debut in ''[[Student of the Year]]'' (2012). They have since worked with Dharma Productions multiple times, with Bhatt starring in nine more of their films.\n| footer_align = center\n| width    = 150\n}}\n[[File:Ayan M Jio-MAMI-Film-Club.jpg|right|thumb|150px|[[Ayan Mukerji]] directed the {{INRConvert|3.2|b}} grossing ''[[Yeh Jawaani Hai Deewani]]'' (2013).<ref name=\"The Indian Express\">{{cite news|title=Yeh Jawaani Hai Deewani is Ranbir Kapoor, Deepika Padukone's biggest hit |url=http://archive.indianexpress.com/news/yeh-jawaani-hai-deewani-is-ranbir-kapoor-deepika-padukone-s-biggest-hit/1127672/ |accessdate=1 July 2013 |work=The Indian Express |date=1 July 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222152212/http://archive.indianexpress.com/news/yeh-jawaani-hai-deewani-is-ranbir-kapoor-deepika-padukone-s-biggest-hit/1127672/ |archivedate=22 February 2014 }}</ref>]]\n[[File:Ranbir Kapoor promoting Bombay Velvet.jpg|right|thumb|150px|[[Ranbir Kapoor]] has collaborated with the company on two top-grossing productions{{mdash}}''[[Yeh Jawaani Hai Deewani]]'' (2013) and ''[[Ae Dil Hai Mushkil]]'' (2016).<ref name=\"alltime\"/>]]\n{{multiple image\n| align     = right\n| direction = vertical\n| image1    = Gauri Shinde.jpg\n| alt1      =\n| image2    = Gulzar with daughter Meghna Gulzar (cropped).jpg\n| alt2      =\n| footer    = [[Gauri Shinde]] (top) and [[Meghna Gulzar]] are among four women who have directed films for Dharma Productions.\n| footer_align = center\n| width    = 150\n}}\n[[File:Janhvi Kapoor graces their Mumbai reception (80) (cropped).jpg|right|thumb|150px|[[Janhvi Kapoor]] made her acting debut with ''[[Dhadak]]'' (2018) and has collaborated with the company two more times]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Key\n| style=\"background:#FFFFCC;\"| {{dagger|alt=Films that have not yet been released}}\n| Denotes films that have not yet been released\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\" style=\"width: 80%; text-align: center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" | Director\n! scope = \"col\" | Producer(s)\n! scope=\"col\" | Cast\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | Synopsis\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | {{Abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Dostana (1980 film)|Dostana]]''\n|1980\n|{{sortname|Raj|Khosla}}\n| {{sortname|Yash|Johar}}\n|[[Amitabh Bachchan]], [[Shatrughan Sinha]], [[Zeenat Aman]]\n| A police officer and a lawyer are best friends. Trouble arises when they both fall in love with the same girl.\n|<ref>{{cite web|title=Dostana (1980) |url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/moviemicro/cast/id/538483 |publisher=Bollywood Hungama |accessdate=20 January 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150120114614/http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/moviemicro/cast/id/538483 |archivedate=20 January 2015 }}</ref>\n|-\n\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Duniya (1984 film)|Duniya]]''\n|1984\n|{{sortname|Ramesh|Talwar}}\n| {{sortname|Yash|Johar}}\n|[[Dilip Kumar]], [[Rishi Kapoor]], [[Amrita Singh]], [[Saira Banu]]\n| An honest man is wrongly imprisoned by criminals. He later avenges his humiliation with the help of a man who was hired by the criminals to spy on him.\n|<ref name=\"Narwekar2012\">{{cite book|last=Narwekar|first=Sanjit |title=Dilip Kumar The Last Emperor|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ub6eAwAAQBAJ&pg=PT180|date=21 December 2012|publisher=Rupa Publications|isbn=978-81-291-3365-6|page=180}}</ref>\n|-\n\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Muqaddar Ka Faisla]]''\n|1987\n|{{sortname|Prakash|Mehra}}\n| {{sortname|Yash|Johar}}\n|[[Raaj Kumar]], [[Raakhee]], [[Raj Babbar]], [[Meenakshi Seshadri]], [[Tina Munim]]\n| A Hindu priest is wrongly imprisoned for rape. When he returns from prison, he tries to locate his family and exact revenge for his humiliation.\n|<ref>{{cite web|title=Muqaddar Ka Faisla (1987) |url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/moviemicro/cast/id/508047 |publisher=Bollywood Hungama |accessdate=20 January 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150120122742/http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/moviemicro/cast/id/508047 |archivedate=20 January 2015 }}</ref>\n|-\n\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Agneepath (1990 film)|Agneepath]]''\n|1990\n|{{sortname|Mukul S.|Anand}}\n| {{sortname|Yash|Johar}}\n|[[Amitabh Bachchan]], [[Mithun Chakraborty]], [[Danny Denzongpa]], [[Madhavi (actress)|Madhavi]]\n| A common man seeks revenge from an unscrupulous man for wrongly framing and murdering his father.\n|<ref>{{cite web|title=Agneepath (1990) |url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/moviemicro/cast/id/533266 |publisher=Bollywood Hungama |accessdate=20 January 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150120123747/http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/moviemicro/cast/id/533266 |archivedate=20 January 2015 }}</ref>\n|-\n\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Gumrah (1993 film)|Gumrah]]''\n|1993\n|{{sortname|Mahesh|Bhatt}}\n| {{sortname|Yash|Johar}}\n|[[Sridevi]], [[Sanjay Dutt]], [[Rahul Roy]]\n| An aspiring singer is wrongly accused of drug trafficking, and is sent to prison. She escapes, and seeks revenge from the people who framed her.\n|<ref>{{cite web|title=Gumrah (1993) |url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/moviemicro/cast/id/539412 |publisher=Bollywood Hungama |accessdate=20 January 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150120122034/http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/moviemicro/cast/id/539412 |archivedate=20 January 2015 }}</ref>\n|-\n\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Duplicate (1998 film)|Duplicate]]''\n|1998\n|{{sortname|Mahesh|Bhatt}}\n|{{sortname|Yash|Johar}}\n|[[Shah Rukh Khan]], [[Juhi Chawla]], [[Sonali Bendre]]\n| An aspiring chef is the doppelganger of a gangster. Comic situations arise when they mistakenly swap places with each other.\n|<ref>{{cite web|title=Shahrukh Khan Remembers His Happiest Film |url=http://www.indiatimes.com/entertainment/bollywood/shahrukh-khan-remembers-his-happiest-film-146832.html |publisher=[[Indiatimes]] |date=8 May 2014 |accessdate=20 January 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150120123945/http://www.indiatimes.com/entertainment/bollywood/shahrukh-khan-remembers-his-happiest-film-146832.html |archivedate=20 January 2015 }}</ref><br /><ref>{{cite news|title=Comic-book charm |url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/film-review-duplicate-starring-shah-rukh-khan-juhi-chawla-sonali-bendre/1/264225.html |author=Chopra, Anupama |date=18 May 1998 |work=[[India Today]] |accessdate=1 July 2013 |url-status=live |archive