illboardhot100|14|artist=Megan Thee Stallion|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 14, 2020|refname=Hot 100}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Billboardrandbhiphop|7|artist=Megan Thee Stallion|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Billboardrhythmic|25|artist=Megan Thee Stallion|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| US [[Rolling Stone Top 100|''Rolling Stone'' Top 100]]<ref name=\"RS 100\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/charts/songs/2020-04-01/|title=Top 100 Songs|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=April 2, 2020|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n| 6\n|}\n\n==Release history==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n! scope=\"col\"| Region\n! scope=\"col\"| Date\n! scope=\"col\"| Format\n! scope=\"col\"| Label\n! scope=\"col\"| {{abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Various\n| March 6, 2020\n| {{hlist|[[Music download|Digital download]]|[[Streaming media|streaming]]}}\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 1501 Certified [[300 Entertainment|300]] ([[Warner Music Group|Warner]])\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/savage/1501734515?i=1501734796|title=Savage by Megan Thee Stallion on Apple Music|via=[[Apple Music]]|date=March 6, 2020|accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| United States\n| April 7, 2020\n| [[Contemporary hit radio|Top 40 radio]]\n|<ref name=\"AllAccess\" />\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Megan Thee Stallion}}\n\n[[Category:Megan Thee Stallion songs]]\n[[Category:2020 singles]]\n[[Category:2020 songs]]\n[[Category:TikTok songs]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by J. White Did It]]\n", "name_user": "Ss112", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCharts:updated", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Savage_(Megan_Thee_Stallion_song)"}
{"title_page": "Mugwort", "text_new": "{{for|the common European species of mugwort|Artemisia vulgaris}}\n[[Image:Artemisia vulgaris - K\u00f6hler\u2013s Medizinal-Pflanzen-016.jpg|thumb|right| Illustration of ''[[Artemisia vulgaris]]'' (1897)]]\n\n'''Mugwort''' is a [[common name]] for several species of aromatic plants in the genus ''[[Artemisia (genus)|Artemisia]].'' In Europe, mugwort most often refers to the species ''[[Artemisia vulgaris]]'', or common mugwort. While other species are sometimes referred to by more specific common names, they may be called simply \"mugwort\" in many contexts.\n\n==Etymology==\nThe Anglo-Saxon ''[[Nine Herbs Charm]]'' mentions {{lang|ang|mucgwyrt}}. A [[folk etymology]], based on coincidental sounds, derives ''{{linktext|mugwort}}'' from the word \"mug\"; more certainly, it has been used in flavoring drinks at least since the early [[Iron Age]].<ref name=\"Physnews1\">{{cite journal| last = Edwards| first = Lin| title = Brewery from 500 BC reveals its secrets| journal = Archeology & Fossils| publisher = Physics News| date = 17 January 2011| url = http://www.physorg.com/news/2011-01-brewery-bc-reveals-secrets.html| doi = 10.1007/s12520-010-0049-5| accessdate =17 January 2011}}</ref> Other sources say ''mugwort'' is derived from the [[Old Norse]] ''muggi'' (meaning \"marsh\") and [[Germanic languages|German]] ''wuertz'' (''wort'' in English, originally meaning \"root\"), which refers to its use since ancient times to repel insects, especially [[moth]]s.<ref>Lust, J. (2005) ''The Herb Book'' 604.</ref>\nThe [[Old English]] word for mugwort is {{lang|ang|mucgwyrt}} where {{lang|ang|mucg-}}, could be a variation of the Old English word for \"[[midge]]\": {{lang|ang|mycg}}. ''[[wikt:wort|Wort]]'' comes from the Old English {{lang|ang|wyrt}} (root/herb/plant), which is related to the [[Old High German]] ''wurz'' (root) and the Old Norse ''urt'' (plant).<ref>''Merriam Webster Dictionary''</ref>\n\n==Species==\nSpecies in the genus ''[[Artemisia (genus)|Artemisia]]'' called mugwort include:\n* ''[[Artemisia argyi]]'' \u2013 Chinese mugwort, used in [[traditional Chinese medicine]]\n* ''[[Artemisia douglasiana]]'' \u2013 Douglas mugwort or California mugwort, native to western North America\n* ''[[Artemisia glacialis]]'' \u2013 alpine mugwort\n* ''[[Artemisia indica]]'' \u2013 Oriental mugwort\n* ''[[Artemisia japonica]]'' \u2013 Japanese mugwort\n* ''[[Artemisia lactiflora]]'' - White mugwort\n* ''[[Artemisia norvegica]]'' \u2013 Norwegian mugwort\n* ''[[Artemisia princeps]]'' \u2013 Korean mugwort (''ssuk''), Japanese mugwort (''yomogi''), used as a culinary herb and in traditional Chinese medicine.\n* ''[[Artemisia stelleriana]]'' \u2013 hoary mugwort\n* ''[[Artemisia verlotiorum]]'' \u2013 Chinese mugwort\n* ''[[Artemisia vulgaris]]'' \u2013 common mugwort, used as a culinary herb and medicinally throughout the world\n\n==Uses==\nMugwort oil contains [[thujone]], which is toxic in large amounts or under prolonged intake. Thujone is also present in ''[[Thuja plicata]]'' (western red cedar), from which the name is derived. The downy hairs on the underside of the leaves can be scraped off and used as effective [[tinder]].<ref>Johnson. C. P. The Useful Plants of Great Britain.</ref> All parts of the plant contain [[essential oils]] with all-purpose insecticidal properties (especially in the killing of insect [[larvae]]).<ref>Duke. J. A. and Ayensu. E. S. Medicinal Plants of China</ref><ref>Allardice.P. A - Z of Companion Planting.</ref> This is best used in a weak [[infusion]], but use on garden plants is not recommended, as it also reduces plant growth.<ref>Riotte. L. Companion Planting for Successful Gardening.</ref> Mugwort has been used therapeutically to relieve sleepiness.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Wild flowers|last=Sarah.|first=Raven|date=2011|publisher=Bloomsbury|others=Buckley, Jonathan.|isbn=9781408813942|location=London|oclc=756273214}}</ref>\n\n===Food===\nThe leaves and buds, best picked shortly before mugwort flowers in July to September, can be used as a bitter flavoring agent to season fat, meat and fish.<ref>\"A Historical Dictionary of the World's Plant Foods: M-Q.\" Cambridge World History of Food, edited by Kenneth F. Kiple and Kriemhild Conee Ornelas, vol. 2, Cambridge University Press, 2000, pp. 1804-1841. Gale Virtual Reference Library, http://link.galegroup.com.erl.lib.byu.edu/apps/doc/CX3450400202/GVRL?u=byuprovo&sid=GVRL&xid=7f5cc15a. Accessed 3 Dec. 2018.</ref> Mugwort has also been used to flavor beer before the introduction of [[hops]].<ref name=\"Physnews1\"/><ref>Llewellyn's 2010 Herbal Almanac by Llewellyn</ref>\n\n===Essential oil===\nThe composition of mugwort [[essential oil]] can vary depending on the genus of plant selected, its habitat, as well as the part of the plant extracted and the season of its harvest. Its main components can include [[camphor]], [[cineole]], \u03b1- and \u03b2-[[thujone]], artemisia ketone (CAS: 546-49-6), [[borneol]] and bornyl acetate as well as a wide variety of other [[phenol]]s, [[terpenes]] and aliphatic compounds.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Abad|first1=Mar\u00eda Jos\u00e9|last2=Bedoya|first2=Luis Miguel|last3=Apaza|first3=Luis|last4=Bermejo|first4=Paulina|title=The Artemisia L. Genus: A Review of Bioactive Essential Oils|journal=Molecules|date=2 March 2012|volume=17|issue=12|pages=2542\u20132566|doi=10.3390/molecules17032542|pmid=22388966|pmc=6268508}} {{open access}}</ref>\n\n===Medieval Europe===\nIn the European Middle Ages, mugwort was used as a magical protective herb. Mugwort was used to repel insects \u2013 especially moths \u2013 from gardens. Mugwort has also been used from ancient times as a remedy against fatigue and to protect travelers against evil spirits and wild animals. Roman soldiers put mugwort in their sandals to protect their feet against fatigue.<ref>{{cite book |last = Wright |first = Colin, Ed. | title = Artemisia |publisher = Taylor & Francis |year = 2002 |location = London; New York |page = 144 |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=t0MtnKDvLLwC&pg=PA144&lpg=PA144&dq=roman+soldiers+mugwort |id = |isbn = 0-415-27212-2}}</ref> Mugwort is one of the nine herbs invoked in the [[Anglo-Saxon paganism|pagan Anglo-Saxon]] ''[[Nine Herbs Charm]]'', recorded in the 10th century in the Lacnunga.<ref>Stephen Pollington \"Leechcraft: Early English Charms, Plantlore and Healing\"</ref>\nGrieve's ''Modern Herbal'' (1931) states that \"in the Middle Ages, the plant was known as {{lang|la|cingulum Sancti Johannis}}, it being believed that [[John the Baptist]] wore a girdle of it in the wilderness...a crown made from its sprays was worn on St. John's Eve to gain security from evil possession, and in Holland and Germany one of its names is 'St. John's plant', because of the belief that \u2013 if gathered on St. John's Eve \u2013 it gave protection against diseases and misfortunes.\"<ref>{{cite book|title=A Modern Herbal: The Medicinal, Culinary, Cosmetic and Economic Properties, Cultivation and Folk-lore of Herbs, Grasses, Fungi, Shrubs, & Trees with All Their Modern Scientific Uses, Volume 2|author=Grieve, Maud|year=1971}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[Isle of Man]], mugwort is known as ''bollan bane'', and is still worn on the lapel at the [[Tynwald Day]] celebrations, which also have strong associations with St John.\n\n===China===\nThere are several references to the Chinese using mugwort in [[Chinese cuisine|cuisine]]. The famous Chinese poet [[S\u016b Sh\u00ec]] in the 11th century mentioned it in one of his poems. There are even older poems and songs that can be tracked back to 3 BC. It was often called {{lang|zh-latn-pinyin|l\u00f3uh\u0101o}} ({{lang|zh|\u848c\u84bf}}) or {{lang|zh-latn-pinyin|\u00e0ic\u01ceo}} ({{lang|zh|\u827e\u8349}}) in Mandarin. Mugwort can be prepared as a cold dish or can be [[stir fry|stir-fried]] with fresh or smoked meat. The [[Hakka]] [[Taiwanese cuisine|Taiwanese]] also use it to make ''[[chh\u00fa-khak-k\u00e9]]'' ({{lang|zh|\u9f20\u9eb9\u7cbf}}), doughy sweet dumplings. Mugwort is also used as a flavoring and colorant for a seasonal rice dish.<ref>{{cite web|title=A Bite of China: The Story of Staple Food|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PCgYUKPNCug|accessdate=20 February 2013|language=Chinese}}</ref>\n\nIn [[traditional Chinese medicine]], mugwort is used in a pulverized and aged form \u2013 called ''{{linktext|moxa}}'' in English (from Japanese ''mogusa'') \u2013 to perform [[moxibustion]], that is, to burn on specific [[acupuncture point]]s on the patient's body to achieve therapeutic effects.\n\n===Germany===\nIn Germany, known as {{wikt-lang|de|Beifu\u00df}}, it is mainly used to [[seasoning|season]] goose, especially the roast goose traditionally eaten for Christmas.\n\n===Japan===\nMugwort \u2013 or {{nihongo||\u84ec|[[yomogi]]}} \u2013 is used in a number of Japanese dishes, including ''[[y\u014dkan]]'', a dessert, or ''[[kusa mochi]]'', also known as ''yomogi [[mochi]]''.\n\nMugwort [[rice cake]]s, or ''kusa mochi'' are used for Japanese sweets called ''[[daifuku]]'' (literally 'great luck'). To make these, take a small amount of mochi and stuff it or wrap it round a filling of fruit or sweetened [[adzuki]] (red bean) paste. Traditional ''daifuku'' can be pale green, white or pale pink and are covered in a fine layer of [[potato starch]] to prevent sticking.\n\nMugwort is a vital ingredient of ''kusa mochi'' (rice cake with mugwort) and ''hishi mochi'' (lozenge rice cake), which is served at the [[Doll Festival]] in March. In addition, the fuzz on the underside of the mugwort leaves is gathered and used in [[moxibustion]]. In some regions in Japan,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shejapan.com/jtyeholder/jtye/living/wagashi/wagashi3.html|title=YOMOGI|first=KAMANEKO WORKSHOP K.Okaeda|last=Kamaneko@msn.com|website=www.shejapan.com|accessdate=29 June 2017}}</ref> there is an ancient custom of hanging ''yomogi'' and [[iris (plant)|iris]] leaves together outside homes in order to keep evil spirits away. It is said that evil spirits dislike their smell. The juice is said to be effective at stopping bleeding, lowering fevers and purging the stomach of impurities. It can also be boiled and taken to relieve colds and coughs.\n\n===Korea===\nIn both [[North Korea|North]] and [[South Korea]], mugwort \u2013 {{transl|ko|ssuk}} ({{lang|ko|\uc465}}) \u2013 is used in soups and salads. A traditional soup containing mugwort and clams is {{transl|ko|ssukguk}} ({{lang|ko|\uc465\uad6d}}), made in spring from the young plants just before they bloom. Another dish is named {{transl|ko|ssukbeomul}} ({{lang|ko|\uc465\ubc84\ubb3c}}), in which the mugwort is mixed with [[rice flour]], sugar, salt and water and is then steamed.\n\nIt is a common ingredient in [[rice cake]]s, teas, [[soup]]s, and [[pancake]]s. \nKnown as a blood cleanser, it is believed to have different medicinal properties depending on the region it is collected in. In some regions, mugwort thins the blood, while in another region, it is claimed to have [[hallucinogen]]ic properties, causing some to pass out from direct skin contact (dermal absorption) with the active chemicals. For this reason, some Koreans also wear a silk sleeve when picking mugwort plants.\n\nIts primary use, however, is in [[Traditional Korean medicine|moxibustion]]. Mugwort is burned on pressure points of the body, much like acupuncture.\n\n==Allergen==\nMugwort pollen is one of the main sources of [[hay fever]] and allergic [[asthma]] in North Europe, North America and parts of Asia.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Art v 1, the major allergen of mugwort pollen, is a modular glycoprotein with a defensin\u2010like and a hydroxyproline\u2010rich domain|journal=The FASEB Journal|volume=17|issue=1|pages=106\u20138|pmid=12475905|year=2003|last1=Himly|first1=M.|last2=Jahn-Schmid|first2=B.|last3=Dedic|first3=A.|last4=Kelemen|first4=P.|last5=Wopfner|first5=N.|last6=Altmann|first6=F.|last7=Van Ree|first7=R.|last8=Briza|first8=P.|last9=Richter|first9=K.|last10=Ebner|first10=C.|last11=Ferreira|first11=F.|doi=10.1096/fj.02-0472fje|doi-access=free}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.weather.com/outlook/health/allergies/common/allergens/AK-allergen-192?from=allergy_allergenstate_more |title=Archived copy |website=Weather Channel |accessdate=2012-11-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120309155119/http://www.weather.com/outlook/health/allergies/common/allergens/AK-allergen-192?from=allergy_allergenstate_more |archivedate=2012-03-09 }}</ref> Mugwort pollen generally travels less than 2,000 meters.<ref name=\"allergia.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.allergia.com/index.phtml?s=849 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-11-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090216232405/http://www.allergia.com/index.phtml?s=849 |archivedate=2009-02-16 }}</ref> The highest concentration of mugwort pollen is generally found between 9 and 11&nbsp;am. The Finnish allergy association recommends tearing as a method of eradicating mugwort.<ref name=\"allergia.com\"/> Tearing mugwort is known to lessen the effect of the allergy, since the pollen flies only a short distance.<ref name=\"allergia.com\"/>\n\n===Medicinal===\n[[File:Detail of mugwort mature leaf.jpg|thumbnail|185px|A mugwort leaf with the pointed leaves characteristic of a mature plant]]\nThe mugwort plant has been used as an [[anthelminthic]], so it is sometimes confused with wormwood (''[[Artemisia absinthium]]''). The plant, called ''n\u0101gadaman\u012b'' in [[Sanskrit]], is used in [[Ayurveda]] for cardiac complaints as well as feelings of unease, unwellness, and general malaise.<ref>Ramawat, K. G., Ed. (2004). ''Biotechnology of Medicinal Plants: Vitalizer and Therapeutic'' Enfield, New Hampshire: Science Publishers, Inc. 5.</ref>\n\nIn [[traditional Chinese medicine]], there is a belief that [[moxibustion]] of mugwort is effective at increasing the cephalic positioning of fetuses who were in a [[breech birth|breech position]] before the intervention. A [[Cochrane review]] in 2012 found that moxibustion may be beneficial in reducing the need for [[External cephalic version|ECV]], but stressed a need for well-designed randomised controlled trials to evaluate this usage.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Coyle ME, Smith CA, Peat B |title=Cephalic version by moxibustion for breech presentation |journal=Cochrane Database Syst Rev |volume=5 |issue= 5|pages=CD003928 |year=2012 |pmid=22592693 |doi=10.1002/14651858.CD003928.pub3}}</ref>\n\nMugworts are used medicinally, especially in Chinese, Japanese, and Korean traditional medicine. One species, ''[[Artemisia argyi]]'', is often called \"mugwort\" in the context of [[traditional Chinese medicine]], or more specifically \"Chinese mugwort\", or {{lang|zh-latn-pinyin|\u00e0ic\u01ceo}} ({{lang|zh|\u827e\u8349}}) in [[Mandarin Chinese|Mandarin]]. ''[[Artemisia princeps]]'' is Korean mugwort, known locally as {{transl|ko|ssuk}} ({{lang|ko|\uc465}}).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.forest.go.kr/kna/special/download/English_Names_for_Korean_Native_Plants.pdf|title=English Names for Korean Native Plants|publisher=|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170525105020/http://www.forest.go.kr/kna/special/download/English_Names_for_Korean_Native_Plants.pdf|archivedate=25 May 2017}}</ref> It is also found in Japan, where it is known as {{transl|ja|yomogi}} ({{lang|ja-Kana|\u30e8\u30e2\u30ae}}).\n\nIndigenous peoples of North America used mugwort for a number of medicinal purposes. Strong, bitter-tasting pasture sagewort tea was taken to treat colds, and fevers. Mugwort was used in washes and salves to treat bruises, itching, sores, poison ivy,  eczema and underarm or foot odour. The leaves were dried, crushed and used as a snuff to relieve congestion, nosebleeds and headaches. Tarragon plants were boiled to make washes and poultices for treating swollen feet and legs and snow blindness. Some tribes called western mugwort 'womens sage' because the leaf tea was taken to correct menstrual irregularity. It was taken to relieve indigestion, coughs, and chest infections. Western mugwort smoke was used to disinfect contaminated areas and revive patients from comas. Northern wormwood tea was taken to relieve difficulties with urination or bowel movements, to ease delivery of babies and to cause abortions.<ref>https://www.amazon.ca/Edible-Medicinal-Plants-Canada-MacKinnon/dp/1551055724</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of plants known as mugwort]]\n*[[Epazote]], a plant with a similar flavour profile used in North and South American cuisines.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Herbs & spices}}\n\n[[Category:Abortifacients]]\n[[Category:Herbs]]\n[[Category:Medicinal plants]]\n[[Category:Witchcraft]]\n[[Category:Plant common names]]\n\n[[zh:\u827e\u8349]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the common European species of mugwort|Artemisia vulgaris}}\n[[Image:Artemisia vulgaris - K\u00f6hler\u2013s Medizinal-Pflanzen-016.jpg|thumb|right| Illustration of ''[[Artemisia vulgaris]]'' (1897)]]\n\n'''Mugwort''' is a [[common name]] for several species of aromatic plants in the genus ''[[Artemisia (genus)|Artemisia]].'' In Europe, mugwort most often refers to the species ''[[Artemisia vulgaris]]'', or common mugwort. While other species are sometimes referred to by more specific common names, they may be called simply \"mugwort\" in many contexts.\n\n==Etymology==\nThe Anglo-Saxon ''[[Nine Herbs Charm]]'' mentions {{lang|ang|mucgwyrt}}. A [[folk etymology]], based on coincidental sounds, derives ''{{linktext|mugwort}}'' from the word \"mug\"; more certainly, it has been used in flavoring drinks at least since the early [[Iron Age]].<ref name=\"Physnews1\">{{cite journal| last = Edwards| first = Lin| title = Brewery from 500 BC reveals its secrets| journal = Archeology & Fossils| publisher = Physics News| date = 17 January 2011| url = http://www.physorg.com/news/2011-01-brewery-bc-reveals-secrets.html| doi = 10.1007/s12520-010-0049-5| accessdate =17 January 2011}}</ref> Other sources say ''mugwort'' is derived from the [[Old Norse]] ''muggi'' (meaning \"marsh\") and [[Germanic languages|German]] ''wuertz'' (''wort'' in English, originally meaning \"root\"), which refers to its use since ancient times to repel insects, especially [[moth]]s.<ref>Lust, J. (2005) ''The Herb Book'' 604.</ref>\nThe [[Old English]] word for mugwort is {{lang|ang|mucgwyrt}} where {{lang|ang|mucg-}}, could be a variation of the Old English word for \"[[midge]]\": {{lang|ang|mycg}}. ''[[wikt:wort|Wort]]'' comes from the Old English {{lang|ang|wyrt}} (root/herb/plant), which is related to the [[Old High German]] ''wurz'' (root) and the Old Norse ''urt'' (plant).<ref>''Merriam Webster Dictionary''</ref>\n\n==Species==\nSpecies in the genus ''[[Artemisia (genus)|Artemisia]]'' called mugwort include:\n* ''[[Artemisia argyi]]'' \u2013 Chinese mugwort, used in [[traditional Chinese medicine]]\n* ''[[Artemisia douglasiana]]'' \u2013 Douglas mugwort or California mugwort, native to western North America\n* ''[[Artemisia glacialis]]'' \u2013 alpine mugwort\n* ''[[Artemisia indica]]'' \u2013 Oriental mugwort\n* ''[[Artemisia japonica]]'' \u2013 Japanese mugwort\n* ''[[Artemisia lactiflora]]'' - White mugwort\n* ''[[Artemisia norvegica]]'' \u2013 Norwegian mugwort\n* ''[[Artemisia princeps]]'' \u2013 Korean mugwort (''ssuk''), Japanese mugwort (''yomogi''), used as a culinary herb and in traditional Chinese medicine.\n* ''[[Artemisia stelleriana]]'' \u2013 hoary mugwort\n* ''[[Artemisia verlotiorum]]'' \u2013 Chinese mugwort\n* ''[[Artemisia vulgaris]]'' \u2013 common mugwort, used as a culinary herb and medicinally throughout the world\n\n==Uses==\nMugwort oil contains [[thujone]], which is toxic in large amounts or under prolonged intake. Thujone is also present in ''[[Thuja plicata]]'' (western red cedar), from which the name is derived. The downy hairs on the underside of the leaves can be scraped off and used as effective [[tinder]].<ref>Johnson. C. P. The Useful Plants of Great Britain.</ref> All parts of the plant contain [[essential oils]] with all-purpose insecticidal properties (especially in the killing of insect [[larvae]]).<ref>Duke. J. A. and Ayensu. E. S. Medicinal Plants of China</ref><ref>Allardice.P. A - Z of Companion Planting.</ref> This is best used in a weak [[infusion]], but use on garden plants is not recommended, as it also reduces plant growth.<ref>Riotte. L. Companion Planting for Successful Gardening.</ref> Mugwort has been used therapeutically to relieve sleepiness.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Wild flowers|last=Sarah.|first=Raven|date=2011|publisher=Bloomsbury|others=Buckley, Jonathan.|isbn=9781408813942|location=London|oclc=756273214}}</ref>\n\n===Food===\nThe leaves and buds, best picked shortly before mugwort flowers in July to September, can be used as a bitter flavoring agent to season fat, meat and fish.<ref>\"A Historical Dictionary of the World's Plant Foods: M-Q.\" Cambridge World History of Food, edited by Kenneth F. Kiple and Kriemhild Conee Ornelas, vol. 2, Cambridge University Press, 2000, pp. 1804-1841. Gale Virtual Reference Library, http://link.galegroup.com.erl.lib.byu.edu/apps/doc/CX3450400202/GVRL?u=byuprovo&sid=GVRL&xid=7f5cc15a. Accessed 3 Dec. 2018.</ref> Mugwort has also been used to flavor beer before the introduction of [[hops]].<ref name=\"Physnews1\"/><ref>Llewellyn's 2010 Herbal Almanac by Llewellyn</ref>\n\n===Essential oil===\nThe composition of mugwort [[essential oil]] can vary depending on the genus of plant selected, its habitat, as well as the part of the plant extracted and the season of its harvest. Its main components can include [[camphor]], [[cineole]], \u03b1- and \u03b2-[[thujone]], artemisia ketone (CAS: 546-49-6), [[borneol]] and bornyl acetate as well as a wide variety of other [[phenol]]s, [[terpenes]] and aliphatic compounds.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Abad|first1=Mar\u00eda Jos\u00e9|last2=Bedoya|first2=Luis Miguel|last3=Apaza|first3=Luis|last4=Bermejo|first4=Paulina|title=The Artemisia L. Genus: A Review of Bioactive Essential Oils|journal=Molecules|date=2 March 2012|volume=17|issue=12|pages=2542\u20132566|doi=10.3390/molecules17032542|pmid=22388966|pmc=6268508}} {{open access}}</ref>\n\n===Medieval Europe===\nIn the European Middle Ages, mugwort was used as a magical protective herb. Mugwort was used to repel insects \u2013 especially moths \u2013 from gardens. Mugwort has also been used from ancient times as a remedy against fatigue and to protect travelers against evil spirits and wild animals. Roman soldiers put mugwort in their sandals to protect their feet against fatigue.<ref>{{cite book |last = Wright |first = Colin, Ed. | title = Artemisia |publisher = Taylor & Francis |year = 2002 |location = London; New York |page = 144 |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=t0MtnKDvLLwC&pg=PA144&lpg=PA144&dq=roman+soldiers+mugwort |id = |isbn = 0-415-27212-2}}</ref> Mugwort is one of the nine herbs invoked in the [[Anglo-Saxon paganism|pagan Anglo-Saxon]] ''[[Nine Herbs Charm]]'', recorded in the 10th century in the Lacnunga.<ref>Stephen Pollington \"Leechcraft: Early English Charms, Plantlore and Healing\"</ref>\nGrieve's ''Modern Herbal'' (1931) states that \"in the Middle Ages, the plant was known as {{lang|la|cingulum Sancti Johannis}}, it being believed that [[John the Baptist]] wore a girdle of it in the wilderness...a crown made from its sprays was worn on St. John's Eve to gain security from evil possession, and in Holland and Germany one of its names is 'St. John's plant', because of the belief that \u2013 if gathered on St. John's Eve \u2013 it gave protection against diseases and misfortunes.\"<ref>{{cite book|title=A Modern Herbal: The Medicinal, Culinary, Cosmetic and Economic Properties, Cultivation and Folk-lore of Herbs, Grasses, Fungi, Shrubs, & Trees with All Their Modern Scientific Uses, Volume 2|author=Grieve, Maud|year=1971}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[Isle of Man]], mugwort is known as ''bollan bane'', and is still worn on the lapel at the [[Tynwald Day]] celebrations, which also have strong associations with St John.\n\n===China===\nThere are several references to the Chinese using mugwort in [[Chinese cuisine|cuisine]]. The famous Chinese poet [[S\u016b Sh\u00ec]] in the 11th century mentioned it in one of his poems. There are even older poems and songs that can be tracked back to 3 BC. It was often called {{lang|zh-latn-pinyin|l\u00f3uh\u0101o}} ({{lang|zh|\u848c\u84bf}}) or {{lang|zh-latn-pinyin|\u00e0ic\u01ceo}} ({{lang|zh|\u827e\u8349}}) in Mandarin. Mugwort can be prepared as a cold dish or can be [[stir fry|stir-fried]] with fresh or smoked meat. The [[Hakka]] [[Taiwanese cuisine|Taiwanese]] also use it to make ''[[chh\u00fa-khak-k\u00e9]]'' ({{lang|zh|\u9f20\u9eb9\u7cbf}}), doughy sweet dumplings. Mugwort is also used as a flavoring and colorant for a seasonal rice dish.<ref>{{cite web|title=A Bite of China: The Story of Staple Food|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PCgYUKPNCug|accessdate=20 February 2013|language=Chinese}}</ref>\n\nIn [[traditional Chinese medicine]], mugwort is used in a pulverized and aged form \u2013 called ''{{linktext|moxa}}'' in English (from Japanese ''mogusa'') \u2013 to perform [[moxibustion]], that is, to burn on specific [[acupuncture point]]s on the patient's body to achieve therapeutic effects.\n\n===Germany===\nIn Germany, known as {{wikt-lang|de|Beifu\u00df}}, it is mainly used to [[seasoning|season]] goose, especially the roast goose traditionally eaten for Christmas.\n\n===Japan===\nMugwort \u2013 or {{nihongo||\u84ec|[[yomogi]]}} \u2013 is used in a number of Japanese dishes, including ''[[y\u014dkan]]'', a dessert, or ''[[kusa mochi]]'', also known as ''yomogi [[mochi]]''.\n\nMugwort [[rice cake]]s, or ''kusa mochi'' are used for Japanese sweets called ''[[daifuku]]'' (literally 'great luck'). To make these, take a small amount of mochi and stuff it or wrap it round a filling of fruit or sweetened [[adzuki]] (red bean) paste. Traditional ''daifuku'' can be pale green, white or pale pink and are covered in a fine layer of [[potato starch]] to prevent sticking.\n\nMugwort is a vital ingredient of ''kusa mochi'' (rice cake with mugwort) and ''hishi mochi'' (lozenge rice cake), which is served at the [[Doll Festival]] in March. In addition, the fuzz on the underside of the mugwort leaves is gathered and used in [[moxibustion]]. In some regions in Japan,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shejapan.com/jtyeholder/jtye/living/wagashi/wagashi3.html|title=YOMOGI|first=KAMANEKO WORKSHOP K.Okaeda|last=Kamaneko@msn.com|website=www.shejapan.com|accessdate=29 June 2017}}</ref> there is an ancient custom of hanging ''yomogi'' and [[iris (plant)|iris]] leaves together outside homes in order to keep evil spirits away. It is said that evil spirits dislike their smell. The juice is said to be effective at stopping bleeding, lowering fevers and purging the stomach of impurities. It can also be boiled and taken to relieve colds and coughs.\n\n===Korea===\nIn both [[North Korea|North]] and [[South Korea]], mugwort \u2013 {{transl|ko|ssuk}} ({{lang|ko|\uc465}}) \u2013 is used in soups and salads. A traditional soup containing mugwort and clams is {{transl|ko|ssukguk}} ({{lang|ko|\uc465\uad6d}}), made in spring from the young plants just before they bloom. Another dish is named {{transl|ko|ssukbeomul}} ({{lang|ko|\uc465\ubc84\ubb3c}}), in which the mugwort is mixed with [[rice flour]], sugar, salt and water and is then steamed.\n\nIt is a common ingredient in [[rice cake]]s, teas, [[soup]]s, and [[pancake]]s. \nKnown as a blood cleanser, it is believed to have different medicinal properties depending on the region it is collected in. In some regions, mugwort thins the blood, while in another region, it is claimed to have [[hallucinogen]]ic properties, causing some to pass out from direct skin contact (dermal absorption) with the active chemicals. For this reason, some Koreans also wear a silk sleeve when picking mugwort plants.\n\nIts primary use, however, is in [[Traditional Korean medicine|moxibustion]]. Mugwort is burned on pressure points of the body, much like acupuncture.\n\n==Allergen==\nMugwort pollen is one of the main sources of [[hay fever]] and allergic [[asthma]] in North Europe, North America and parts of Asia.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Sign In|journal=FASEB Journal |volume=17|issue=1|pages=106\u20138|pmid=12475905|year=2003|last1=Himly|first1=M.|last2=Jahn-Schmid|first2=B.|last3=Dedic|first3=A.|last4=Kelemen|first4=P.|last5=Wopfner|first5=N.|last6=Altmann|first6=F.|last7=Van Ree|first7=R.|last8=Briza|first8=P.|last9=Richter|first9=K.|last10=Ebner|first10=C.|last11=Ferreira|first11=F.|doi=10.1096/fj.02-0472fje}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.weather.com/outlook/health/allergies/common/allergens/AK-allergen-192?from=allergy_allergenstate_more |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-11-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120309155119/http://www.weather.com/outlook/health/allergies/common/allergens/AK-allergen-192?from=allergy_allergenstate_more |archivedate=2012-03-09 }}</ref> Mugwort pollen generally travels less than 2,000 meters.<ref name=\"allergia.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.allergia.com/index.phtml?s=849 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-11-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090216232405/http://www.allergia.com/index.phtml?s=849 |archivedate=2009-02-16 }}</ref> The highest concentration of mugwort pollen is generally found between 9 and 11&nbsp;am. The Finnish allergy association recommends tearing as a method of eradicating mugwort.<ref name=\"allergia.com\"/> Tearing mugwort is known to lessen the effect of the allergy, since the pollen flies only a short distance.<ref name=\"allergia.com\"/>\n\n===Medicinal===\n[[Image:Detail of mugwort mature leaf.jpg|thumbnail|185px|A mugwort leaf with the pointed leaves characteristic of a mature plant]]\nThe mugwort plant has been used as an [[anthelminthic]], so it is sometimes confused with wormwood (''[[Artemisia absinthium]]''). The plant, called ''n\u0101gadaman\u012b'' in [[Sanskrit]], is used in [[Ayurveda]] for cardiac complaints as well as feelings of unease, unwellness, and general malaise.<ref>Ramawat, K. G., Ed. (2004). ''Biotechnology of Medicinal Plants: Vitalizer and Therapeutic'' Enfield, New Hampshire: Science Publishers, Inc. 5.</ref>\n\nIn [[traditional Chinese medicine]], there is a belief that [[moxibustion]] of mugwort is effective at increasing the cephalic positioning of fetuses who were in a [[breech birth|breech position]] before the intervention. A [[Cochrane review]] in 2012 found that moxibustion may be beneficial in reducing the need for [[External cephalic version|ECV]], but stressed a need for well-designed randomised controlled trials to evaluate this usage.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Coyle ME, Smith CA, Peat B |title=Cephalic version by moxibustion for breech presentation |journal=Cochrane Database Syst Rev |volume=5 |issue= 5|pages=CD003928 |year=2012 |pmid=22592693 |doi=10.1002/14651858.CD003928.pub3}}</ref>\n\nMugworts are used medicinally, especially in Chinese, Japanese, and Korean traditional medicine. One species, ''[[Artemisia argyi]]'', is often called \"mugwort\" in the context of [[traditional Chinese medicine]], or more specifically \"Chinese mugwort\", or {{lang|zh-latn-pinyin|\u00e0ic\u01ceo}} ({{lang|zh|\u827e\u8349}}) in [[Mandarin Chinese|Mandarin]]. ''[[Artemisia princeps]]'' is Korean mugwort, known locally as {{transl|ko|ssuk}} ({{lang|ko|\uc465}}).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.forest.go.kr/kna/special/download/English_Names_for_Korean_Native_Plants.pdf|title=English Names for Korean Native Plants|publisher=|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170525105020/http://www.forest.go.kr/kna/special/download/English_Names_for_Korean_Native_Plants.pdf|archivedate=25 May 2017}}</ref> It is also found in Japan, where it is known as {{transl|ja|yomogi}} ({{lang|ja-Kana|\u30e8\u30e2\u30ae}}).\n\nIndigenous peoples of North America used mugwort for a number of medicinal purposes. Strong, bitter-tasting pasture sagewort tea was taken to treat colds, and fevers. Mugwort was used in washes and salves to treat bruises, itching, sores, poison ivy,  eczema and underarm or foot odour. The leaves were dried, crushed and used as a snuff to relieve congestion, nosebleeds and headaches. Tarragon plants were boiled to make washes and poultices for treating swollen feet and legs and snow blindness. Some tribes called western mugwort 'womens sage' because the leaf tea was taken to correct menstrual irregularity. It was taken to relieve indigestion, coughs, and chest infections. Western mugwort smoke was used to disinfect contaminated areas and revive patients from comas. Northern wormwood tea was taken to relieve difficulties with urination or bowel movements, to ease delivery of babies and to cause abortions.<ref>https://www.amazon.ca/Edible-Medicinal-Plants-Canada-MacKinnon/dp/1551055724</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of plants known as mugwort]]\n*[[Epazote]], a plant with a similar flavour profile used in North and South American cuisines.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Herbs & spices}}\n\n[[Category:Abortifacients]]\n[[Category:Herbs]]\n[[Category:Medicinal plants]]\n[[Category:Witchcraft]]\n[[Category:Plant common names]]\n\n[[zh:\u827e\u8349]]\n", "name_user": "Bsherr", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAllergen:improving citations, changing image to file", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mugwort"}
